Cancer and fertility: ethical and legal challenges.

Robertson JA(1).

Author information:
(1)University of Texas Law School, 727 East Dean Keeton St., Austin, TX 78705, 
USA. jrobertson@mail.law.utexas.edu

Preserving the fertility of younger cancer patients requires coordinated efforts 
and attention to ethical issues by oncologists and fertility specialists. 
Although sperm is easily stored, freezing eggs or ovarian tissue is still 
experimental and should not be offered except as part of an experimental 
protocol. When gametic material is stored for later use, written directives for 
posthumous use may be given effect, and subsequently born children may be 
recognized as legal offspring of the deceased. Concerns about the welfare of 
offspring resulting from an expected shortened life span of the parent are not 
sufficient reason to deny cancer survivors assistance in reproducing.

